### USB Cable
1. Carefully score the cable jacket about 25 mm from the end with a not-too-sharp knife.<br>
   <img src="./image/usb-1-1.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
   2. Peel back the jacket carefully (e.g., with your thumbnail).<br>
      <img src="./image/usb-1-21.png" alt="" height="150"><img src="./image/usb-1-22.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
      3. Carefully unwind the braided shield (mind the sharp wires).<br>
         <img src="./image/usb-1-3.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
         4. Twist the braided shield and unwrap the foil shield.<br>
            <img src="./image/usb-1-4.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
            5. Cut away the filler threads with a knife or side cutters.<br>
               <img src="./image/usb-2-5.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
               6. Tin the end of the twisted shielding braid.<br>
                  <img src="./image/usb-2-6.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
                  7. Strip up to 3 mm of insulation from the colored wires at each end.<br>
                     <img src="./image/usb-2-7.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
                     8. Tin the wire ends (the heat will pull insulation back slightly).<br>
                        <img src="./image/usb-2-8.png" alt="" height="150"><br>
                        9. Solder the USB cable to the PCB.<br>
                           <img src="./image/assembly-kit-site-17.png" alt="" width="500"><br>

                           A good solder joint has a shiny surface when using leaded solder. Lead-free solder always looks matte.  
                           <img src="./image/assembly-kit-site-18.png" alt="" width="500">

                           ### Installing Sensor
                           <img src="./image/assembly-kit-site-19.png" alt="" width="500"><br>
                           > :warning: To prevent damage to the sensor from electrostatic discharge, discharge yourself first—e.g., touch the grounded metal of an outlet or a radiator—before handling the sensor.

                           ## Modifying the Bottom Shell for the Third Button

                           In the right scroll-wheel mount, remove the raised center section at the bottom so the third button can be pressed.  
                           <br><img src="./image/ausbrechen-dritte-taste.png" alt="" height="400">

                           ## Removing the Sensor Film

                           Now carefully peel the protective film off the sensor chip.  
                           <br><img src="./image/Sensor-Folie.webp" alt="" height="400">

                           ## Final Assembly

                           <img src="./image/zusammenbau-1.png" alt="" width="500"><br><br>
                           <img src="./image/zusammenbau-2.png" alt="" width="500"><br><br>
                           <img src="./image/zusammenbau-3.png" alt="" width="500"><br><br>
                           <img src="./image/zusammenbau-4.png" alt="" width="500"><br><br>
                           If everything was done correctly and no shorts were created, you can test the mouse on your PC. You now have a one-of-a-kind, self-assembled 3-button USB mouse!